The paper discusses learning representations from sensorimotor information, which is a common topic in machine learning and artificial intelligence. Specifically, the paper focuses on the integration of sensorimotor information over time, which suggests a focus on learning from sequential data. This makes cs.LG (Machine Learning) the most likely category. The paper also discusses the use of sensory representations for prediction, which suggests a focus on predictive modeling, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) another likely category. The paper also discusses the role of memory and motor information in learning representations, which suggests a focus on robotics and control, making cs.RO (Robotics) a likely category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of sensory representations in computer vision, making cs.CV (Computer Vision) a possible category. The paper also discusses the use of neural networks, which suggests a focus on neural networks and deep learning, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible category.
